0:{"buildId":"q5IOURLFFv9A9k-M0yvw-","rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[["$","article",null,{"className":"bg-white","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 pt-6","children":["$","nav",null,{"className":"flex items-center space-x-2 text-sm text-gray-600","children":[["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/","className":"hover:text-blue-600","children":"Home"}],[["$","div","/car-seats",{"className":"flex items-center space-x-2","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"text-gray-400","children":"/"}],["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/car-seats","className":"hover:text-blue-600","children":"Car Seats"}]]}],["$","div","/car-seats/car-seat-safety-ratings-explained",{"className":"flex items-center space-x-2","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"text-gray-400","children":"/"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-gray-900 font-medium","children":"Car Seat Safety Ratings Explained: NHTSA, IIHS & What Tests Actually Measure"}]]}]]]}]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12 border-b border-gray-200","children":[["$","h1",null,{"className":"text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4","children":"Car Seat Safety Ratings Explained: NHTSA, IIHS & What Tests Actually Measure"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-lg text-gray-600","children":"Understand how car seats are rated for safety. Learn what NHTSA and IIHS testing measures, how to interpret ratings, and which tests matter most."}]]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"prose prose-lg max-w-none text-gray-700","children":[["$","h2","0",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Introduction"}],["$","p","1",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"When shopping for car seats, you'll see references to safety ratings, test results, and organizational acronyms: NHTSA, IIHS, ASTM. These ratings are supposed to help you choose the safest seat, but understanding what each rating actually measures is difficult. Some ratings test crash protection; others test chemical safety. Some tests are mandatory; others are optional. This guide demystifies car seat safety ratings and helps you understand what test results actually mean for your purchase decision."}],["$","h2","2",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"The Organizations Behind Car Seat Ratings"}],["$","h2","3",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#NHTSA (National Highway Traffic Safety Administration)"}],["$","p","4",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**What it is**: The U.S. federal agency responsible for vehicle and child safety seat standards."}],["$","p","5",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**What it does**: Sets the minimum federal safety standards that all car seats sold in the U.S. must meet. Creates and enforces testing protocols."}],["$","p","6",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Important distinction**: NHTSA sets minimum standards. All car seats sold legally meet NHTSA standards. This means NHTSA ratings are a floor, not a differentiator. All car seats are \"NHTSA compliant,\" but some exceed the standard significantly."}],["$","p","7",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**What NHTSA Tests**:\n- **Frontal crash protection** (30 mph frontal collision, the most common severe crash type)\n- **Side-impact protection** (varying impact speeds)\n- **Harness and belt retention** (does the seat hold the child during crash forces?)\n- **Installation stability** (does the seat remain properly positioned during a crash?)"}],["$","p","8",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"All car seats sold in the U.S. must pass these tests. Passing is mandatory; no variations are allowed."}],"$L3","$L4","$L5","$L6","$L7","$L8","$L9","$La","$Lb","$Lc","$Ld","$Le","$Lf","$L10","$L11","$L12","$L13","$L14","$L15","$L16","$L17","$L18","$L19","$L1a","$L1b","$L1c","$L1d","$L1e","$L1f","$L20","$L21","$L22","$L23","$L24","$L25","$L26","$L27","$L28","$L29","$L2a","$L2b","$L2c","$L2d","$L2e","$L2f","$L30","$L31","$L32","$L33","$L34","$L35","$L36","$L37","$L38","$L39","$L3a","$L3b","$L3c","$L3d","$L3e","$L3f","$L40","$L41","$L42","$L43","$L44","$L45","$L46","$L47","$L48","$L49","$L4a","$L4b","$L4c","$L4d","$L4e","$L4f","$L50","$L51","$L52","$L53","$L54","$L55","$L56","$L57","$L58","$L59","$L5a","$L5b","$L5c","$L5d","$L5e"]}]}],"$L5f","$L60"]}],["$L61"],"$L62"]}],"loading":null,"isPartial":false}
3:["$","h2","9",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#IIHS (Insurance Institute for Highway Safety)"}]
4:["$","p","10",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**What it is**: A private, non-profit research organization funded by insurance companies. Not a government agency."}]
5:["$","p","11",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**What it does**: Conducts independent crash testing beyond federal minimums. Creates ratings (similar to vehicle crash test ratings: Good, Acceptable, Marginal, Poor)."}]
6:["$","p","12",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Important distinction**: IIHS testing is voluntary. Manufacturers choose whether to submit car seats for IIHS testing. Only some car seats have IIHS ratings."}]
7:["$","p","13",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**What IIHS Tests**:\n- **Frontal crash** (35 mph, faster than NHTSA's 30 mph standard—simulating more severe crashes)\n- **Side-impact crash** (31 mph side-impact, matching real-world severe crash data)\n- **Rollover behavior** (vehicle roof crush resistance)\n- **Installation ease and user error resistance**\n- **Protection from overheating** (does the seat itself get too hot in sun?)\n- **Chemical safety** (flame retardants, flame testing)"}]
8:["$","p","14",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"IIHS ratings are more rigorous than NHTSA minimums. An \"Acceptable\" IIHS rating means the seat outperforms federal minimum standards."}]
9:["$","h2","15",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#ASTM International"}]
a:["$","p","16",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**What it is**: A voluntary standards organization (not a government agency). Develops voluntary standards for consumer products."}]
b:["$","p","17",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**What it does**: Creates testing protocols that manufacturers can choose to adopt (beyond federal minimums)."}]
c:["$","p","18",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**What ASTM Tests**:\n- **Flammability** (flame resistance of seat materials)\n- **Chemical safety** (off-gassing, flame retardant content)\n- **Special uses** (car seats for premature or low-birth-weight infants)"}]
d:["$","p","19",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"ASTM standards are optional for manufacturers. They provide a framework for those who want to exceed federal minimums."}]
e:["$","h2","20",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Understanding NHTSA Ratings"}]
f:["$","h2","21",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#The Federal Standard (Mandatory for All Seats)"}]
10:["$","p","22",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"All car seats sold in the U.S. undergo NHTSA testing before market release. This testing simulates:"}]
11:["$","p","23",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Frontal Crash (30 mph)**\n- Vehicle hits a fixed barrier at 30 mph (approximately a 15 mph crash into a parked car)\n- A crash test dummy (representing a child) is placed in the car seat\n- Instruments measure forces on the head, neck, chest, and abdomen\n- Tolerance limits are defined: acceptable force ranges that don't exceed injury thresholds"}]
12:["$","p","24",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Side-Impact Crash (18-20 mph)**\n- Vehicle is struck from the side by a moving barrier\n- Dummy experiences lateral force\n- Measurement similar to frontal: forces must remain within acceptable ranges"}]
13:["$","p","25",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Result**: All NHTSA-compliant seats pass these tests. Passing is non-negotiable; no car seat can be sold without passing."}]
14:["$","h2","26",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#What NHTSA Ratings Don't Tell You"}]
15:["$","p","27",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**They don't compare performance**: NHTSA testing is pass/fail, not comparative. You can't say \"Seat A is safer than Seat B\" based on NHTSA ratings alone—both passed the same test."}]
16:["$","p","28",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**They don't reflect real-world crashes**: Testing occurs at specific speeds and angles. Real crashes vary in speed, angle, and force distribution. A crash protection advantage in a 30 mph frontal impact might not generalize to a 40 mph crash or a 20 mph crash."}]
17:["$","p","29",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**They don't account for installation quality**: The test assumes perfect installation. Real-world installations vary in tightness and accuracy. A well-designed seat that's poorly installed provides less protection than design intent."}]
18:["$","p","30",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**They don't measure user error resistance**: Some seats are easier to install correctly than others. NHTSA doesn't rate how easily users can make mistakes."}]
19:["$","h2","31",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Understanding IIHS Ratings"}]
1a:["$","h2","32",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#The Voluntary Standard (Optional; Higher Bar)"}]
1b:["$","p","33",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"IIHS testing is more demanding than NHTSA:"}]
1c:["$","p","34",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Higher crash speeds**: 35 mph frontal (vs. NHTSA's 30 mph) and 31 mph side-impact (vs. NHTSA's 18-20 mph). These speeds better approximate severe real-world crashes."}]
1d:["$","p","35",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**More detailed measurement**: IIHS records head injury criteria (HIC) scores—a mathematical measure of the severity of head acceleration. Lower HIC scores indicate better protection."}]
1e:["$","p","36",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Comparative ratings**: IIHS assigns ratings: Good, Acceptable, Marginal, Poor. This allows comparison between seats."}]
1f:["$","h2","37",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#IIHS Rating Meanings"}]
20:["$","p","38",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Good**: Seat excels at crash protection. Head injury criteria well below thresholds. Performance exceeds federal minimums significantly."}]
21:["$","p","39",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Acceptable**: Seat meets federal standards and performs well but doesn't exceed minimums dramatically. Adequate protection but not exceptional."}]
22:["$","p","40",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Marginal**: Seat barely meets federal standards. Performance hovers near acceptable thresholds. Higher crash forces might compromise protection."}]
23:["$","p","41",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Poor**: Seat fails to meet federal standards or barely passes. Performance is questionable."}]
24:["$","h2","42",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#What IIHS Ratings Tell You"}]
25:["$","p","43",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"If a car seat earns a \"Good\" IIHS rating, you know:\n- It passes federal NHTSA standards (all seats do)\n- It exceeds federal standards in higher-speed crash testing\n- It performs better than seats with \"Acceptable\" or lower IIHS ratings\n- The manufacturer cared enough to submit for independent testing"}]
26:["$","p","44",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"If a car seat has no IIHS rating, you can't conclude it's unsafe—only that the manufacturer didn't submit for testing. Many safe, excellent seats lack IIHS ratings because manufacturers don't pursue the certification."}]
27:["$","h2","45",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Real-World Limitations of All Ratings"}]
28:["$","h2","46",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Crash Testing Isn't Real Crashes"}]
29:["$","p","47",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Crash tests use dummies and standardized crash angles/speeds. Real crashes vary:\n- A 35 mph frontal crash at 15 degrees isn't the same as a 35 mph offset crash at 45 degrees\n- A roof-crush scenario (rollover) in a test doesn't perfectly predict behavior in a vehicle with different roof design\n- A head-on collision into a barrier isn't identical to colliding with another vehicle"}]
2a:["$","p","48",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Implication**: A car seat that passes crash testing will likely protect well in real crashes, but the protection is an extrapolation, not a guarantee."}]
2b:["$","h2","49",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Installation Quality Matters as Much as Design"}]
2c:["$","p","50",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"A poorly installed excellent car seat provides less protection than a well-installed mid-range seat. Testing assumes proper installation; reality often includes user error."}]
2d:["$","p","51",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Implication**: The best-rated seat in the world provides no benefit if you install it incorrectly. Correct installation matters as much as choosing the right seat."}]
2e:["$","h2","52",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Child Variability Isn't Fully Captured"}]
2f:["$","p","53",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Testing uses standardized dummies representing \"average\" children of specific weights/heights. Real children vary:\n- A very small or large 2-year-old might not be ideally protected in a test designed for average 2-year-olds\n- Children with different body proportions (longer torsos, shorter legs, etc.) might experience slightly different crash forces"}]
30:["$","p","54",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Implication**: A test result doesn't perfectly predict outcomes for all children, though it's reasonably representative."}]
31:["$","h2","55",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Using Ratings to Choose a Car Seat"}]
32:["$","h2","56",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Step 1: Ensure NHTSA Compliance"}]
33:["$","p","57",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"All legal car seats meet NHTSA standards. This is non-negotiable. No seat should be sold without NHTSA compliance."}]
34:["$","p","58",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Action**: Verify your seat is NHTSA-compliant (check the manufacturer's website or seat documentation)."}]
35:["$","h2","59",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Step 2: Check IIHS Ratings (If Available)"}]
36:["$","p","60",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"If IIHS ratings exist for your seat options:\n- **Good IIHS rating**: Excellent choice. Seat performs well above federal minimums.\n- **Acceptable IIHS rating**: Good choice. Seat meets federal standards with reasonable margin.\n- **Marginal or Poor IIHS rating**: Avoid if better options available. Seat barely meets minimums."}]
37:["$","p","61",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Action**: Visit IIHS.org and search for your specific car seats. Compare ratings among your options."}]
38:["$","h2","62",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Step 3: Evaluate Installation Design"}]
39:["$","p","63",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Beyond test ratings, assess how easily you can install the seat correctly:\n- Does the manual provide clear instructions?\n- Are attachment points clearly marked?\n- Does the seat have an installation indicator (e.g., angle indicator, tightness indicator) to help you get it right?\n- Are there LATCH anchors in your vehicle?"}]
3a:["$","p","64",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Some seats are engineered to be user-friendly; others assume advanced mechanical knowledge."}]
3b:["$","p","65",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Action**: Read customer reviews mentioning installation ease. Try installing a demo unit at a baby store if possible."}]
3c:["$","h2","66",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Step 4: Research Recalls"}]
3d:["$","p","67",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Even excellent seats sometimes have recalls (manufacturing defects, design flaws discovered post-market). Check the NHTSA recall database."}]
3e:["$","p","68",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Action**: Visit NHTSA.gov, search for your seat's brand and model, and check for open recalls."}]
3f:["$","h2","69",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Step 5: Consider Features Beyond Crash Protection"}]
40:["$","ul","70",{"className":"list-disc list-inside my-4 space-y-1","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"text-gray-700","children":"**Ease of cleaning**: Removable, washable liners? Dishwasher-safe trays?"}],["$","li","1",{"className":"text-gray-700","children":"**Ease of adjustment**: How hard is it to change harness height or adjust recline?"}],["$","li","2",{"className":"text-gray-700","children":"**Compatibility**: Does it work with your vehicle? Your stroller (if relevant)?"}],["$","li","3",{"className":"text-gray-700","children":"**Longevity**: How long does it serve (infant-only vs. convertible vs. convertible + booster)?"}]]}]
41:["$","p","71",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Crash protection is paramount, but daily usability matters too. A seat that passes tests but creates friction in daily use might lead to incorrect installation or safety shortcuts."}]
42:["$","h2","72",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Common Misunderstandings About Safety Ratings"}]
43:["$","h2","73",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Misunderstanding #1: \"All NHTSA-Compliant Seats Are Equally Safe\""}]
44:["$","p","74",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**The Truth**: All NHTSA-compliant seats meet minimum federal standards. Some exceed standards significantly (evident from IIHS ratings), while others just barely pass. NHTSA compliance is a floor, not a ceiling."}]
45:["$","p","75",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Implication**: Choose seats with additional safety certifications (IIHS ratings) if available. Don't assume all compliant seats are equal."}]
46:["$","h2","76",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Misunderstanding #2: \"No IIHS Rating Means the Seat Is Unsafe\""}]
47:["$","p","77",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**The Truth**: IIHS testing is voluntary. Excellent, safe seats might lack IIHS ratings because manufacturers didn't pursue certification."}]
48:["$","p","78",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Implication**: A seat without an IIHS rating isn't automatically worse. However, if comparing two similar seats and one has an IIHS \"Good\" rating while the other has no rating, the rated seat has proven higher performance."}]
49:["$","h2","79",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Misunderstanding #3: \"Expensive Seats Are Safer\""}]
4a:["$","p","80",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**The Truth**: Price and safety are loosely correlated. Expensive seats often have better materials, longer lifespan, or more features—not necessarily better crash protection."}]
4b:["$","p","81",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Implication**: An $150 seat with a good IIHS rating is safer than a $400 seat with no rating. Don't assume price equals safety."}]
4c:["$","h2","82",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Misunderstanding #4: \"Newer Models Are Always Safer\""}]
4d:["$","p","83",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**The Truth**: Newer designs sometimes improve on older models, but not always. An older model that's well-established and refined might perform as well as a newer design."}]
4e:["$","p","84",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Implication**: Check IIHS ratings and recalls for both old and new models. Newer doesn't automatically mean safer."}]
4f:["$","h2","85",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"How to Find Safety Information"}]
50:["$","p","86",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**NHTSA Compliance**: Listed on the car seat documentation and manufacturer website (usually in the manual)"}]
51:["$","p","87",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**NHTSA Recalls**: Visit NHTSA.gov, search your seat's model, and check \"Complaints\" and \"Recalls\" tabs"}]
52:["$","p","88",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**IIHS Ratings**: Visit IIHS.org, navigate to \"Car Seats,\" search your seat model, and view ratings"}]
53:["$","p","89",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Manufacturer Documentation**: Owner's manual and website often include test data and certifications"}]
54:["$","p","90",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Third-Party Reviews**: Read customer reviews on Amazon, Buy Buy Baby, or parenting forums—note comments about installation ease and real-world reliability"}]
55:["$","h2","91",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Questions to Ask Before Buying"}]
56:["$","p","92",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"1. **Does this seat have an IIHS rating? If so, what is it?**\n   - Good: Excellent\n   - Acceptable: Good\n   - No rating: Unknown (might still be safe; research further)"}]
57:["$","p","93",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"2. **Are there any open recalls for this model?**\n   - No recalls: Good\n   - Minor recalls (unrelated to crash protection): Generally okay\n   - Major recalls (harness, stability): Reconsider"}]
58:["$","p","94",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"3. **How many customers report installation ease?**\n   - Most positive: Good design\n   - Mixed reviews: Potential user error risk\n   - Negative reviews: Avoid if alternatives exist"}]
59:["$","p","95",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"4. **Does my vehicle have LATCH anchors in the rear center or side?**\n   - Yes: LATCH installation is straightforward\n   - No: Seatbelt installation (slightly more complex)"}]
5a:["$","p","96",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"5. **How long does this seat serve my child?**\n   - Infant-only (birth-12 months): $150-$300; buy convertible if planning future children\n   - Convertible (birth-5 years): $250-$400; best value for long-term use\n   - Convertible + booster (birth-12 years): Rare; all-in-one options exist but sacrifice specialized design"}]
5b:["$","h2","97",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Conclusion"}]
5c:["$","p","98",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Car seat safety ratings are useful but not comprehensive. NHTSA compliance ensures minimum safety standards; IIHS ratings indicate above-average performance. However, no rating replaces proper installation, regular inspection, and understanding your specific car seat's features."}]
5d:["$","p","99",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"When choosing a car seat, prioritize:\n1. NHTSA compliance (mandatory)\n2. IIHS rating (if available; prefer \"Good\" or \"Acceptable\")\n3. Installation ease (design that reduces user error)\n4. Recall history (check NHTSA database)\n5. Specific features (compatibility, longevity, ease of use)"}]
5e:["$","p","100",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"A seat with an excellent IIHS rating installed correctly will provide superior protection to an untested seat installed poorly. Buy the best-rated seat you can afford, install it correctly, and verify installation before every drive. That discipline matters more than selecting between nearly-equivalent certified seats."}]
5f:["$","$L63",null,{"pagePath":"/car-seats/car-seat-safety-ratings-explained","siteName":"thefamilypick"}]
60:["$","section",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8 border-t border-gray-200","children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/car-seats","className":"inline-block bg-blue-600 text-white px-6 py-2 rounded font-semibold hover:bg-blue-700","children":"Back to Car Seats Comparison"}]}]
61:["$","script","script-0",{"src":"/_next/static/chunks/5935fefdd9fc8f83.js","async":true}]
62:["$","$L64",null,{"children":["$","$65",null,{"name":"Next.MetadataOutlet","children":"$@66"}]}]
66:null
